04209nam a22005295i 9780300242232DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221996ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002422327 a10.12987/97803002422322doi  a(DE-B1597)625831  a(OCoLC)1322123919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aB783.Z7bO7313 1996eb 7aSCI0250002bisacsh04a1952221 aOrdine, Nuccio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGiordano Bruno and the Philosophy of the Ass /cNuccio Ordine. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource :b23 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- t1 Bruno and the Ass: A Long-Deferred Questlon -- t2 Myths, Fables, Tales: The "Asinine" Materials -- t3 The Ass and Mercury: A Key to Coincidentla Oppositorum -- t4 The Ambiguous Space of Asininity -- t5 Man and the Ass, between "Bestiality" and "Divinity" -- t6 Positive Asininity Toil, Humility, Tolerance -- t7 Negative Asininity: Idleness, Arrogance, Unidimensionality -- t8 The Oration of Fortune -- t9 In the Labyrinth of Truth -- t10 From Orion to Chiron: Opposing Images of the Religious Cult -- t11 The Ass in the Guise of the Sileni: Appearances Are Deceptive -- t12 The Literature of the Ass before Bruno -- t13 The Entropy of Writing -- t14 Natural Science and Human Science: A "Nouvelle Alliance" -- tIconographical Collection -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this highly original study, Nuccio Ordine uses the figure of the ass as a lens through which to focus on the thought and writings of the great Renaissance humanist philosopher Giordano Bruno. The donkey played a prominent role as a symbol in sixteenth-century literature, and for Bruno the ass and human asininity became a recurring motif in his writings. Ordine offers the first analysis of Bruno's use of this complex symbol, which encompasses contradictory characteristics ranging from humble and hardworking to ignorant and idle. The result is a deeper understanding of Bruno the philosopher, along with a stronger appreciation of Bruno the literary artist.Ordine looks especially closely at Bruno's use of the figure of the donkey in his attacks on the theologies of both the Reformation and the Counter Reformation, and in issues that have become modernist concerns. Ordine's analysis sheds light on each of the major themes of Bruno's philosophy: science and knowledge, myth and religion, language and literature.Widely acclaimed when it was first published in Italian in 1987, Ordine's book is now available in English for the first time, bringing his intriguing insights to a new readership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDonkeysxMiscellanea. 0aMental efficiencyxHistoryy16th century. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Zoology / Entomology.2bisacsh1 aGarin, Eugenio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311053801440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300242232?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300242232423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300242232/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles